target: You bear the Brand of the Tempered Flame. Your devotion to the Pyres grants you control over an otherworldly magic.
Adds powerful spells your card pool.
You bear the Brand of the Concerned Doctors. Use the technological marvels of traps and machines to your advantage.
Adds traps and machinations to your pool.

Some use separate bins for organization. Others will place records into random piles and claim the system only “lives in their head.” Personally, I prefer drawers adorned with precise labels. The Wurmkin use stones with empty slots to keep their Echoes close and contained. What a wonder it is to learn of these civilizations that have developed without our hands to influence...or corrupt.
Tethys and I created this Seal to commemorate the founding of the Stygian Guard and the protection they are sworn to give to their Unnamed Titan.
Prior to the Covenant, the creation of these Pyre artifacts was commonplace, but dangerous. This led to widespread chaos and the eventual creation of the Covenant.

The coveted Light of Seraph. Those from above worship it as much as we value the Pyre. From what I’ve seen it’s powerful, sure, but it’s not as special as they say. That doesn’t mean I won’t take some if given the chance.

Herzal, my first friend. I can never forgive myself for what they did to you, nor for allowing it to happen. With all my remaining strength, I will never let harm fall upon Heph. I promise this to you, Herzal.

I like to think that, over time, I’ve become more empathetic to decisions made that I may not make myself. The Spine Chief’s decision to keep the Wurmkin hidden for all these years is one of those decisions — one I would not make, but I understand. Empathy, however, does not require respect.

After the Pyrestone brace proved to be wildly successful, Seraph stole my design and created a similar device to infuse the stones with Light instead. As is his way, he created a housing much more ostentatious than the simple one I created for Hell.
After Seraph invaded Hell, Fel left me to support his cause much more eagerly than I'd expected. Before she left, Fel gave me this stave to assist in the fights ahead. I never saw her again.

My discovery of the creation of Pyrestones, gemstones infused with flames of the Pyre, was monumental in enhancing the strength of Hell’s forces and marked a turning point in the war against Heaven. That victory was short-lived, however, as the design was stolen and copied shortly thereafter.
A discarded mask of the shadow known as Penumbra. I’ve encountered several of these throughout the mines. The shadow seems to outgrow them quickly.

When I finally succeeded in uniting all nine Rings of Hell, we created a united army of Hell to fight back in the event of the Covenant breaking. I was surprised at the overwhelming support I received in this endeavor.

It seems that the energy of the Cuttlehex and the Molluscmages does not die with them, but continues to surge through their beards so long as they are kept intact. I've kept some of the beards with me. They've been quite useful, but the tentacles make me a tad squeamish.

When the Rail was built, the Crucible became accessible to Hellborne other than the Umbra Shroud. The Shroud was not too welcoming, however, and crafted lights of shadow that only they could use to see, making it impossible for tourists to linger.

One more recent Wurmkin experiment has been to propagate an Echo's stored knowledge. This involves taking a small shard of a source and placing it into a shallow plate of water. Some amount of knowledge is maintained in the newly formed crystal, but not yet enough to make the process widely adopted.
The stairwells of the Boneshaker are never what they seem. Among other surprises, the hidden spike traps I've engineered can be set to stop any combatant.

What’s the point of this struggle between Heaven and Hell if we’re caught up in this endless cycle anyway? Cycles were meant to be broken, just like rules! Even if I were the one to invent those rules...
In a scheme I refused to take part in, Flicker devised a plan to collect funds from Waxers to benefit those who have passed, only to keep them for himself.

During my time in Heaven, I was gifted some of their purifying water, but the liquid was so strong that it would burn anything it touched. So, I put it aside. It has now found a new use as a repellant in the Boneshaker.

By the time you read this, I hope that Hell, or what remains of it, remains a united front against their invaders. But this was not always the case. The destruction of Divinities had left souls to wander endlessly and the absence of Judgement meant that all realms felt the effects of overcrowding and resource shortages. In some ways, this time before the war was even more trying than the ensuing violence.
Too often, the seemingly extinguished coals of the Boneshaker still smolder, most likely powered by the Pyre. Unfortunately, this has led to many explosive accidents on my train.
Breaking through their armor is considered a rite of passage for the Awoken, marking their shift from Hollow to Animus. This old armor breaks under the weight of new vines making up the Animus.
When Seraph shattered our Hell Pyre and Hell froze over, many unsuspecting imps were caught in the ice. Taken aboard the Boneshaker, the Pyre shard slowly melts them free.

I modified the Pyre so that the sound it makes when it is threatened can no longer be heard by any creature, in Heaven or in Hell. However, an unintended consequence has been obsverved: distant Pyre shards will resonate with the same frequency and vibrate wildly, sometimes even shattering.

Intruders often try to tap the Wildwood to harvest its sap, though the Wildwood usually ends up harvesting the intruders instead. The Edge Priory has allowed me to collect these taps for my own personal research.

As a symbolic sacrifice to convince her fellow sea dwellers of her commitment to the Covenant and the confinement of the Titan, Tethys removed her own scales. I don't understand their ways, but the gesture worked as she intended.

When the Divinities come back, and they will, you must accept the Pact they put forth. It will make things harder. It may make time act...strange. But each Shard given out of their gratitude is a piece of Divinity itself and will offer some protection. This will buy you time, and that’s all it seems I am fit to provide anymore. But, perhaps, that will be enough.
When Fel left to join her cause, she left me with remaining Embers of the Pyre. She could have been killed for this, but she gave them anyway. That’s all I have to say about Fel.

Our time together was brief, but our bond was unbreakable. However, when the Covenant was broken, my hope for what was unbreakable was shattered as well. I keep her gift close to my heart to remember what we had and what was lost.

While the Umbra doesn’t appear to become inebriated like other denizens of Hell, they’ve still taken to processing Void Shards into a liquid that mildly dulls the senses. When the Shroud consumes it, the drink makes them somewhat less unpleasant in my dealings with them.

I should no longer be surprised by Fade’s unusual nature. Her lack of wax dates her long before the creation of the Waxers and the Wickless, and the wicks atop her head seem to be purely ornamental. Yet the knife she carries and the “code” that she lives by, or lack thereof, has many similarities to the Remnant of today.

Not all who enter the mold do so willingly. The need for restraints, while I consider it cruel, has been effective in solidifying these participants' will to reform or, sometimes, to melt for the sake of others.

Despite the failings of the Roles of Champions, there was some small peace to be found in the knowledge that the Exiles had made an almost identical decision when defending themselves against greater powers. Though, their failing has only amplified ours.

Times are changing. Divinities are making rules while we keep trying to save our own skins. Well, not anymore. There’s more souls out there who can help us, there’s got to be. And it’s about time someone set out to find them. So, I guess, this is where I’ll try and record that search. I’ll bet old Herzal’s turning in his ice at the thought. Don’t worry, I fail like the best of ‘em.
As elusive as their name, these bright flowers bloom briefly in the cracked soil of the Scorched Plains, quickly smothered by the harsh environment.

According to the Hellhorned, the dead are never really gone. Their remains are cremated and used as warpaint to imbue warriors with great strength and remind them of their eventual return to the ground.

When a Hellhorned defeats another in battle, they will break off the loser’s horns and add it to their collection, forming them into a crown. I've learned the hard way that asking to wear another's crown is considered incredibly rude.

Created for more urgent circumstances, the Wickless granted me this bomb for an emergency supply of wax on detonation. Having no need for it, I ended up giving it to the Waxers to increase their chances of survival.

Ice created from the water of the Styx Sea melts at much higher temperatures than other ice I’ve found throughout Hell. Any icicles that form on the Boneshaker while in this Ring will not thaw entirely from the train’s residual heat, and will become potential hazards for negligent bystanders.
There was little time to act after Seraph’s invasion, but there was just enough for me to design a way to protect what would remain of the Pyre after its inevitable destruction.
A tool made of petrified Wildwood bark, used to heat ores into something stronger. Used by the Edge Priory to create armor for their Hollows, a process that astounds me still.

Eggs are rarely hatched as soon as they are created. In fact, new eggs have not been laid for centuries. So the dormant eggs are incubated in calcified Kinhost carapace. Though, if no new eggs exist, I suspect that the Wurmkin’s sudden announcement of their existence is less selfless than they’d have me believe.
I can use this alloy to fortify the Pyre brace in the Boneshaker and make it stronger. But I need to remember to use this material economically, as it is hard to come by.

Our initial calls for support were a little… wordy: “We, the 9 Rings of Hell and the residents therein, declare our sovereignty from the Heavenly invaders of our lands. As fellow Hellborne, we implore you to consider supporting our shared cause and ensure our survival lest we cease to exist entirely.” It is comforting to know that I've matured from needless description and flourish to a paragon of simplicity.

The Bogwurm is mentioned very casually among the Wurmkin. So much so that I often forgot the beast was a Titan. But it seems that the Bogwurm that gave them life and shelter is so present in their everyday routines, that their eternal devotion to study is reverence enough to the Titan. Even if they do refer to the Bogwurm as “that ghastly old worm” more than I care to acknowledge.

Supposedly, these crystal “Shardsouls” once contained sacrificed souls and were created by the Exiles in a gambit to save Heaven, Hell, and Human. Now empty, the crystal’s remains house many Morsels. This may confirm my theory that the Umbra Shroud is made of pure soul.

Once the Rail was complete, I returned to the Crucible to enlist the Shroud’s help to create the Boneshaker. When the last bolt was punched into the train, they drove one last spike into the Rail to memorialize the train’s departure.

From my studies of the Stygian totems, I’ve found that the sidestones that circle around them help to focus their energy. When removed from their totem host, these sidestones can produce a similar, though much weaker, effect on their target.
Railhammers have been forged in the deep pits of the Scorched Plains since the founding of our Covenant, making them durable tools in the construction of Hellhorned armor.
For all their faults and treacherous tendencies, the Winged excel at developing new technology. Lucky for us, Antumbra Morsels were able to steal some of it for our collective benefit.
These immense jacks are used to prevent the Crucible from collapsing. At the speed the Umbra seems to be mining it, I’m not sure these jacks will help it.

This fungal infection affects the bark of trees throughout the Wildwood. While it feeds on much of the sap the tree produces, the fungus also accelerates the tree's sap production entirely, creating a fascinating symbiotic relationship between the two species.

I can no longer remember the specifics of when I first came to Hell or called it my home. The centuries have deteriorated my mind's ability to remember. Though, through the haze, I can still feel the complete and consuming warmth of the Pyre.

While trying to improve the efficiency of energy transfer from the Pyre to the Boneshaker, I inadvertently created a way to convert the energy directly into steam. At the time it seemed like a failure, but it may well prove useful in these harsh times.
When we imprisoned the Titan for the safety of Hell, the Stygian Guard stripped it of its name. When the Titan is released again, its name will return with it.

This book shall provide a detailed recollection of my time in Heaven and Hell in my pursuit of the Rail of the Covenant and the brokering of a lasting peace to save our two realms. Should I fail, look here to learn from those who’ve come before.

Ember is rarely observed in between states of living and dying, making it challenging to learn what destroys its lifeforce. The fragments are volatile things, guided entirely by how much they like their owner.

It seems that throughout the existence of the Waxen Arches, everything has fallen victim to wax encasement. Not even the Ember of the Pyre has been spared, though I've collected any I've seen trapped to free them again later.
When the Covenant was formed, Seraph made a diplomatic offering to the Titan at my suggestion. It should have been telling that the pearl immediately turned black when the Traitor touched it.

As the Winged offensive grew more aggressive and building materials grew more scarce, I had to develop some protection with the tools at hand. These walls won’t withstand more than a couple blows, but that can still mean the difference between life and death.
These Pyre circlets were gifted by the Winged to commemorate the binding of the Covenant. Now that the Covenant has broken, it is only fair that I pass them on to the Champions of Hell.

Collaboration between the Rings of Hell was rare, but the few that did occur produced wondrous results. Water from the Stygian Sea blessed by the Channelers of the Wildwood created a solution capable of soothing the pains of Heaven’s wretched sinner contraptions. However, this was used only a handful of times. Those contraptions rarely had survivors...

Just before the Freeze, I was working on an upgraded version of the Train Stewards. The invasion of the Winged interrupted my research and prevented me from rolling out the upgrade to each Steward on the Boneshaker, but I’ve kept the prototype around in the hopes of eventually finishing what I started.

These ancient scrolls detail the laws of the Guard, from ceremonial offerings to mundane dress codes. They are a historical treasure trove that I look forward to studying more when this whole affair is finished.

Seraph was not always the Traitor he is today, hellbent on the unification of Heaven and Hell for our mutual survival. He was the main reason the Covenant was pursued to begin with. I suppose his need for control finally got the better of him...
My heart and my life. I only hope that you can learn from an old man’s mistakes.

Their time in Hell has dulled the Winged’s ability to exert moderation in their consumption. They frequently binge on the bounty they’ve conquered, which is good for us, as it often leads to lethargy in battle.
The first to hammer the Rail of the Covenant. It served me well, but the time it spent with the Pyre filled it with an energy that is too powerful to contain.
The seaweed of the Sea is known to be very resistent to breaking. The addition of Stygian sigils make breaking it impossible, despite all my efforts.
My failed attempt at refocusing the light of the Pyre to better fuel the Boneshaker. It wasn’t entirely a waste of time though, as the lens was able to refract that energy back onto the Pyre itself.

As invasions of the Boneshaker have become more frequent, I’ve devised a number of traps and devices to subdue any unwanted guests. These cages should hold them back temporarily when they board the train.

Before the Covenant, Hell had become so dangerous that I made my living creating armor for its unlucky residents. Seraph and I pursued the Covenant to quell the unrest and the armor persisted across centuries. It has proven useful in this last fight.
Flicker has been known to imbibe on occasion, and when he can't find me to drink with him, he'll corner unlucky Waxers who quickly succumb to its effects.

As much as it pained me to see the tools of my trade used for such barbaric purposes, the war effort for Hell was in dire need of support. The forges quickly devolved into needless bickering between clans, each one claiming to be the best. Like children, I had to separate them for their own safety and my sanity.
I have yet to hear of a sinner from Hell released from the confines of Penance. It seems that the Winged have a skewed sense of morality when it comes to those outside their kind.

An Echo with no knowledge is just another piece of rock. At least, that’s what the Wurmkin would have you believe. The way they toss around empty Echoes, their knowledge retrieved, makes me wonder if their so-called reverence for knowledge has been emphasized for their own egos.
An ancient heart, petrified in the woods of the Wildwood. It still beats coldly. Endlessly.

We amassed what small gold we had over time, all of it plundered from the rarely-defeated Heavenly forces in hopes of stifling their war funding. Given the great wealth of Heaven, however, I don’t imagine they even noticed. It’s funny how quickly the afraid will empty their pockets in the off chance of retaining some control of their sanity.

The coveted Light of Seraph. Those from above worship it as much as we value the Pyre. From what I’ve seen it’s powerful, sure, but it’s not as special as they say. That doesn’t mean I won’t take some if given the chance.

The carving of stoneform is a long and tedious process, not entirely suitable for capturing fleeting thought. Some Wurmkin have created small Echo necklaces to preserve their knowledge on the fly, storing their observations directly onto the small crystal. Still, most of the clan finds the practice irreverent.
There are more victims in mine collapses than I would’ve first thought. Many Umbra have fallen victim to these accidents and while they fade back into the shadow, their teeth remain.
One of the first instruments I developed for the Boneshaker. Regrettably, it’s not very accurate and delivers entirely random heat output from the furnace.

With each melt and reform comes the development of new resin, giving the Waxer a particular edge they didn't have in their previous life. I've chipped some away to study further once aboard the Boneshaker.

I constructed the train with what I had at the time, with hopes to expand later on with what I’d scavenge on the way. To make sure the creatures of Hell would all fit, I had to sacrifice the size of the furnaces. No more!

For the Hellhorned that are considered too violent by their own clan’s standards, imprisonment is a cruel affair. Subjected to rot in chains sunk directly into the bubbling lava below, the prisoners are burned by the molten steel that binds them... and the scorching heat only enrages them further.

My time has come to an end. Hell fades into the cold as the Covenant and Rail are no longer intact. The Boneshaker is ready to take Hell and its Champions through the wasteland and succeed where I have failed. May this hammer serve as a reminder of the peace that could exist and the promise that can be forged again.

Wurmkin do not sleep. Underground, day and night are merely talked about in the academic sense. As such, Wurmkin will study for days, sometimes weeks, without interruption, so direct contact between Wurmkin is rare. Instead, the Wurmkin use open stone walls as notice boards.

Waters touched by fragments of the lost Divinities show us reflections of another world. A world where the Divine Mother governed over the creation of life and the responsibility of death. Given the purview of her powers, it follows that her destruction created the many immortal beings of Heaven and Hell and led to our current predicament.
One of my crowning achievements. A metal-based compound that can be formed into any shape. I’ve only been able to create a small batch of it, but a little goes a long way.

The roles of the Champions of Hell were created as part of the Hellpact. They were to be representatives of each clan, chosen by their own clan. In hindsight, this was an ambitious idea that failed more often than it succeeded. It’s unfair to attribute our current situation to these failings, but that makes it no less accurate.
When Fel left to join her cause, she left me with remaining Embers of the Pyre. She could have been killed for this, but she gave them anyway. That’s all I have to say about Fel.
Though credited with building the Hellhorned’s section of the Rail, Grrrg wasn’t able to complete it without help from other demons. Some needed more motivation than others.
I've never found the final whereabouts of Grrrg, but before his mysterious disappearance, he left his unbroken horn with the Hellhorned, leading me to believe he has succumbed to death.

Not all of the Edge Priory endeavors have been successes. Their attempts to return to the physical form of an Animus have been met with countless failures. The vines they’ve used in these experiments wither with the unstable energy that’s cursed them.

An imp officially matures into a demon when their tail falls off and they learn to stand on their own feet, but this evolution only seems to enrage the demon further. I don't like the sight of the disembodied tails, but keeping them is necessary.

Traveling to the Bogs now, one would not be faulted for missing the conflict between the Wurmkin and the Kinhost. In fact, one would even surmise that no conflict exists at all, and in many ways, it doesn’t. I suppose the Wurmkin’s swift removal of any Kinhost dissent, or small display of sentience for that matter, has squashed any lingering division. Not quite what I’d consider a victory.
The sharp claws of the Titan. They were lodged into the stone as the Titan tried to escape prison we'd built for it. Now, they serve as a reminder of the strength we locked away.

Keys to Votive Houses have secretly circulated in Waxer communities for eons, with new copies being made all the time to evade detection of the original thief. Having come across a couple in my travels, I've kept them for myself in case the need for one arises.

Wyldenten speaks in these visions of the Exiles' purpose to forestall the Divinities desertion and avoid Armageddon. This history has been lost to time, it seems, as we’ve only created this new destruction ourselves.

Uniting the Rings of Hell to construct the Rail was no easy task, but after years of work I was finally able to achieve what was once thought impossible by having the clans from each Ring all agree to this pact.
Of the same ilk as the Pyre, these coldstones have been transformed by the freezing of Hell. They now emanate icy frost instead of Hellish heat.
Truly an unusual fellow, this Dante, but he’s proven useful on so many occasions that his allegiance can hardly be questioned.
One of my crowning achievements. A metal-based compound that can be formed into any shape. I’ve only been able to create a small batch of it, but a little goes a long way.

Despite my several attempts to win the support of the furry traders, the merchants of Hell have decided to stay neutral. Finally, after much pestering, they allowed me into their guild. That hasn’t stopped them from wringing me of any spare coin.
Using the smithing techniques I taught them, the Edge Priory developed casings for the thorns ejected from the Awoken, turning them into much deadlier weapons against the Winged.

From what I can gather, the Queen had the only full-grown Demon tail in existence. Yet, in the visions I’ve spent with her, this tail has been replaced by her Shardsoul tail. Did this replacement grant the Hellhorned the ability to cycle, making them immortal? It’s as if a large shadow looms over any memory I should have of these Exiles...

After a thorn has lodged into the ground and released its spores, it will wilt and return to the Wildwood. On very rare occasions, the thorn will produce a fruit that is coveted among Channelers, though I find it personally much too sour.

Contrary to common belief, demons do not travel light. Supposedly, the souls of Heaven and Hell require less worldly attachments than the Humans they consider to be so lowly, but I can tell you that is absolutely untrue. I once saw a Hellhorned Demon bring aboard six bursting suitcases. When I asked if all of it was needed, the Demon only glared and growled. Only then, have I truly known fear.
The Winged crafted a solid piece of steel to show me the creation process. The runes they placed on it made sure I could not melt it down again for my own use.

When Flicker decided to help me unite the Ring and build the Rail, he lit a ceremonial candle to commemorate the event. Appropriately, the current state of the candle reflects the state of the Covenant it was created to represent.
I found this Morsel abandoned in the mines of the Crucible with all of its appendages missing. It seems to have taken a liking to me.

Rumblings of Seraph’s moral absolutism had become frequent in the time before Heaven’s invasion. Transgressions were rarely tolerated and often met with swift physical punishment. I can see now that his invasion of Hell was largely driven by some personal vendetta against me and my failings.

For the less committed Wickless enthusiasts who are unwilling to remove their wick entirely, the snuffer provides a glimpse into a possible wick-free life. I've helped some Waxers dim their flames, though most prefer to do it themselves.

The armies of Heaven were able to board our train today... while it was moving! I’d be astonished at the concept if I weren’t preoccupied with the implications of this feat. Our end may be nearing faster than I’d hoped.

Echoes are the essence of Divinity. There is no recorded history of this, and, frankly, anyone claiming this fact would be considered mad. But given my recent... revelations... I can say without a doubt that their origin is Divine.

On the rare occasion that a member of the Shroud has lost their teeth, sharp dentures are created from Crucible gems. Due to their high value, this has led to many Umbra intentionally removing their teeth.
Herzal always talked about Judgement and the struggles of mankind. Well, they wouldn't have so many struggles if they were invincible! And so it was done. Just like that. You're welcome, humans!
Their coin has no value here. What better use is there than to pelt the Winged with it?

Never before have the nine Rings of Hell collaborated on something as monumental as the Rail of the Covenant. As a token of thanks, I created these amulets through my time in Hell, imbuing them with some basic power, and I gave them to each clan.

Wurmkin learning to master stoneform carving are often given a set of claw covers to practice. This allows them to practice stoneform etchings without a worry of damaging their own claws. Given how sturdy I've seen Wurmkin claws to be, I'd guess this "protection" is little more than vanity.
The roots of the Wildwood spread farther than just their own Ring, but the farther they travel from the center of the wood, the more likely they are to wither and die.

For as long as I’ve lived in Hell, I’ve known the Ring filled with Bogwurm remains to be a desolate place with no sentient inhabitants. When Solgard mentioned a Kinstone gifted to him by a clan that resides there, the Wurmkin, I realized there’s so much I still don't know about this place. Or, perhaps, I can no longer remember.

I once asked Herzal to craft me some invincible armor. After three months of nonstop work, he presented me with the most beautiful helmet I had ever seen. I then immediately broke it. So much for invincibility!
Picture this scenario: You die, go to the Afterlife, and live forevermore. Fantastic! Except now I’ve made it so you can die again. What even happens if you die twice? I have yet to die once!
After completing the Rail, I destroyed the anvil I used to create all the Railspikes as a symbolic ending to this endeavor.

Before the Edge Priory became the reclusive group they are now, they would channel their energy into steel lockets that could be worn by their Awoken Hollow protectors, allowing the Hollows to gain more strength at the cost of their longevity.

A cloak gifted to me from a Channeler of the Edge Priory. It still contains some residual energy from its owner, allowing anyone who wears it to heal their wounds more effectively. Though this energy is not without side effects...

Steel hammered in the heat of the Scorched Plains is easily recognized by its banding. After the freeze, the steel became in short supply, but I’ve still been able to stockpile a small amount for defensive enhancements.
Only the wealthiest of Waxers can afford the portable melting pot I created to allow on-demand wax guttering. Out of charity, unfortunate Tombs are given a spout by the Reformed so they can survive.
One bored evening I asked myself, “What would happen if the rain was poison?” So I made the rain poison. Then Bogwurm threatened to eat me. Horrifying, but worth it.

The bogs and decay on the Ring’s topside acts as a sort of camouflage for those within and a deterrent from anyone wanting to investigate further. I’ve seen bodies decomposed in minutes on more than one occasion. So, I wouldn’t say I was excited to return to the bogs for any reason.
Clipped Wings are discarded after removal to suppress any hope of the victim’s redemption. However, I was able to smuggle some out of Heaven disguised as Waxer rags.

I constructed this as a gift to Penumbra for his help with the Covenant. The necklace is made out of the finest gems found in the Crucible. For whatever reason, Penumbra tossed it aside, perhaps considering it too gaudy.

target:
Combat previews are now enabled.

The preview number shows the amount of damage each unit will take during the next combat phase. A red X means the unit will be defeated.

Daedalus is the strongest boss you've faced yet!

He moves between floors freely, but can be attacked if you clear out other enemies on that floor.

Each floor of the train has limited capacity.

The amount of space a unit will take up is indicated by the number of [capacity] pips on its card.
Build up Charged Echoes [corrupt] to empower Wurmkin units and spells on that floor. [corrupt] that exceed the available [emptycorrupt] will disappear at the end of turn.

Once you end your turn, combat plays out automatically.

First, enemies attack the friendly unit closest to them. Then, any friendly units who survived the attack get to hit back!

You've unlocked your first Covenant!

Each Covenant enables new features and increases the challenge. Keep winning runs to unlock them all!
Are you sure you want to end the turn without playing your champion?

Enemies have boarded your train!

Enemies enter at the lowest level and move up one level every turn. If they reach the top, they’ll attack your Pyre!

Some spells can only be played once per battle.

Cards with Consume are placed in the consume pile when played. They will not be available again until the next battle.

Summon units to defend your train!

You can play each unit card once per battle.

Take on Pact Shards [crystal] in exchange for rewards. The more you have, the more powerful your enemies will grow. If you defeat Seraph with 100[crystal] or more, you will unlock the true final battle.
Play Infused cards to add [corrupt] to that floor. The Wurmkin's starting artifact, Wurmtooth, applies Infused to starter cards and one card per draft.
This room has reached the unit limit on one of its sides. For that side, effects like [ascend] and [descend] will fail. If the enemy side is full, enemies moving up the train will bypass the room.

Hell Rush is a timed multiplayer mode which includes all clans. You haven’t unlocked all the clans yet in Singleplayer, so you may be faced with unfamiliar decisions under pressure.

Are you sure you want to proceed?

Protect your Pyre!

This is your Pyre. If it takes too much damage from enemy attacks, your run is over.

Defeat the boss to win the battle!

His {0} ability means that combat will continue in this room until you or he is defeated.

Want to speed up combat?

Use the Game Speed button in the top right to toggle the speed.

Undergo trials for greater risk and reward!

Activating the trial will make this battle more difficult, but you'll earn an extra reward if you win.

Watch out for Triggers!

This bomb has a triggered ability and will explode on its turn, dealing damage.

Check the tooltips of units with a purple trigger icon to see the details of their abilities.

Welcome to Hell! Your train is carrying precious cargo: the last remaining shard of the Pyre, needed to relight the fires in the depths of Hell.

Invaders from Heaven, the Winged, will do anything to prevent you from completing your journey. You must make wise decisions and build up your band of monsters to have any hope of success. Good luck, Hellborne!

target: The end of the world turned out to be a mostly quiet affair.
Hell has finally frozen over, its nine gates now controlled by the Seraph and the Gilded Wings.
All across the planes, the Dominion is unraveling.
The few remaining Monsters of Hell now band together for one final stand to reclaim their underworld.
Aboard their fearsome train the Bone Shaker, they ride through the Dominion to re-ignite the dormant flames of Hell.
The End of the World is just beginning.

target: Sacrifice a unit to infuse its essence into another unit.

The Last Divinity’s grasp on our realm is slipping, so the Wurmkin claim. Yet, if endangered, the Divinity will collapse time upon itself, creating a sort of infinite cycle of defeat. We’ve faced Divinities before, but I cannot comprehend defeating a Being whose strength at its weakest can still warp the flow of time on a whim.
Guardian at the edge. This Hollow is close to becoming steel itself.

Said to be among the great Titans that formed the Rings of Hell, the Bogwurm had long since died by the time I began to build the Rail. The Bogwurm's remains have created a Ring full of waste and ruin, perfect for the inhabitants of Hell.

These sharp cliffs have led to the demise of many souls. Most who come to Hell hope to bring their previous wealth, but material riches make navigation of the treacherous cliffside path a dangerous affair.
Precious metals can be uncovered in the mines of the Crucible, mined by the Umbra Shroud and its Antumbra Morsels. The tunnels are far and twisting. Few living creatures know their complete range.

Once the glowing seat of the Pyre, the heart of Hell has become a frozen reminder of the invasion and the destruction of the Pyre. Seraph sits on the extinguished remains, awaiting our return and hoping to wipe us out for good.

This wasteland has always been the desolate crossing into Hell. It serves as a buffer, the first Ring of Hell, and the only separation from Heaven. The ice only turned an endless desert into an endless tundra.

Formed by the Pyre's awesome might, this Ring is the volcanic homeland of the Hellhorned demons. Deep fissures reveal the untold strength of the Pyre that tore them open. In these war-torn plains, the Winged invasion destroyed the last resistance of Hell in the battle now known as Armageddon.

The Stygian Guard protects the depths of Hell from their post underneath the Styx Sea. Now frozen, the sea is covered in ice, trapping the Unnamed Titan within. The Unnamed Titan still sleeps for now, but as the ice melts, it will not stay trapped forever.

Across this waxen landscape, ever-growing arches can be seen, made of the remains of the Melting Remnant souls who've climbed to the top in search of rumored wealth. The survivors built Votive Houses throughout the Ring. The houses serve as sanctuaries for those who hope to melt faster, or not to melt at all.

Massives vines took root within this Ring, creating the massive Wildwood Forest that exists today. This living forest traps unsuspecting victims within its vines to absorb their souls into its hivemind of the Awoken.

target: <style="Body">As you pass a <color="yellow">Train Graveyard</color>, you notice several of your fallen allies.

Within the beasts of gnarled steel lie now extinguished Pyre shards. Even further inside the rubble, you can make out some last protected treasures. Perhaps, if you were to relight the Pyre shards using some of your own, the trains would reveal their value.</style>
<style="Prompt">Which of the trains' Pyre shards do you relight?</style>
<style="Body">The Pyre shard flickers to life, the treasure within now revealed as the Pyre removes its final defense.
Yet as you leave, the Pyre shards goes out once more, this time for good. You are all that is left.</style>
Two ornate chests have emerged from the thawing ice...
Both chests have a strange lock mechanism that look like they could be picked with shards from the <style="Pyre">Pyre</style>. The more decorated chest might take a few more tries, though.</style>
<style="Prompt">Do you break off some of your <style="Pyre">Pyre</style> to get what's inside?</style>
<style="Body">The lock clicks after a few attempts, revealing the wealth of contents within.</style>
<style="Body">The smaller chest creaks open and you're rewarded with a few coins.</style>

<style="Body">You use your pick to avoid any unnecessary damage to your Pyre. After opening the second chest, the pick breaks, but with all this newfound gold, you could buy a whole trainfull of picks.</style>
<style="Body">The Boneshaker makes its way through an abandoned <color="red">Trainyard</color>.

The once bustling workshop is now <anim=wave>eerily</anim> silent and empty, picked over by scavengers. Though in the rubble, you're able to make out a couple of things that may be useful: a large <style="Keyword">hook</style> and some quick-release <style="Keyword">doors</style>.</style>
<style="Prompt">Do you salvage anything from the trainyard?</style>

<style="Body">You enlist the help of the crew to install the <style="Keyword">doors</style>, giving you more control over the location of any invaders in the <style="Keyword">Boneshaker</style> via quick <anim=shake>ejection</anim>.</style>

<style="Body">The <style="Keyword">hook</style> is installed in the Boneshaker's Pyre Room, giving you an easy way to drag any invaders upwards and subject them to the power of the <style="Pyre">Pyre</style>.</style>
<style="Body">The train jerks to a halt to avoid the <color="purple">Chaos Portal</color> that spontaneously appeared.</style>
The whirling pit tears apart everything around it, sucking in anything that gets too close.</style>
<style="Body">As if satisfied by your offering, the <style="Keyword">Chaos Portal</style> reverses its pull, <anim=shake>spewing out debris</anim> from all over Hell.
Through the mess, you can clearly see the realms of both the [InkInsert:classname] and the [InkInsert:subclassname]. A brief opening allows you to reach for one.

target: <style="Body">You reach through the portal to the <style="Class1">Scorched Plains</style>, close your hand around something solid, and pull it back through.</style>
<style="Body">You reach through the portal to the <style="Class2">Wildwood Forest</style>, close your hand around something solid, and pull it back through.</style>
<style="Body">You reach through the portal to the <style="Class3">Waxen Arches</style>, close your hand around something solid, and pull it back through.</style>
<style="Body">You reach through the portal to the <style="Class4">Frozen Styx Sea</style>, close your hand around something solid, and pull it back through.</style>
<style="Body">You reach through the portal to the <style="Class5">Crucible</style>, close your hand around something solid, and pull it back through.</style>
<style="Body">You turn to leave, and the <color="purple">Chaos Portal</color> closes as quickly as it appeared.</style>
The Historian makes his way towards the train in his unusual carriage.

“Hellborne, how fortunate am I that our travels have finally crossed paths! I am recording the events of Armageddon for posterity. Possibly futile, I know, but I shall make a fortune if you do, somehow, succeed.”
<style="Prompt">“So, would you characterize yourself as <style="Keyword">honest, aggressive</style>, or <style="Keyword">stealthy</style>?”</style>
<style="Body">“Interesting, indeed. And quite uncharacteristic of <style="Keyword">Hellborne</style>, though by no means unwelcome! Perhaps those good intentions will carry us past these dark times.”
“Here's something for your assistance. Best of luck to you in the battles ahead.”</style>
<style="Body">“Ahh yes, the fabled fighting spirit of the <style="Keyword">Hellborne</style>! I would expect nothing less. Your account shall make for wonderful reading.”
“Sneaky, but smart, I see. Well, I shall have to change the narrative to support the truth, but nothing a few hours of editing can't accomplish.”
<style="Body">A collection of <color="orange">glowing brands</color> are scattered next to a granite crypt.
Each brand bears the mark of one of the clans of Hell. Those of the [InkInsert:nonclasses] seem to be the only ones hot enough to be of use.

The crypt cracks open to reveal a gift from the forgotten denizens of Hell. Even in defeat, it seems, Hell is full of surprises.</style>
<style="Body"><color="red">Heph the Blacksmith</color> huddles near the train. She is clearly unaccustomed to the <anim=shake>cold</anim>.
“I trust the <style="Keyword">Rail</style> has been smooth. Well, as smooth as it can be in times like these...”

I don't have room for them both, but I figure you may have need for one. Hell, I might even be able to upgrade it later if it suits you.”

target: The <style="Keyword">Covenant</style> memorial in the middle is refracted twice by the crystals surrounding it: one <style="Keyword">larger</style>, one <style="Keyword">smaller</style>. In front of each, there are markings for a creature to stand and receive the remaining energy.</style>
There is a blinding flash and earsplitting roar. Where your ally once was now stands a behemoth.
As you depart, the train lurches under the creature's newfound weight.</style>
After a tiny spark of light and a faint squeak, your ally steps away from the crystal much smaller than before.
They're so small, in fact, that you almost missed them entirely before returning to the train.</style>
<style="Body">The crystals' energy fades in acknowledgement of your depature.</style>
<style="Body">Remains of the once great <color="yellow">Rail of the Covenant</color> litter the landscape.
One of the Railspikes still contains some lingering power. You could take it and use it on one of your units or enhance your own magical prowess.
<style="Body">You take the Railspike and apply its remaining power. It seems to only be effective for this final use, as it disintegrates in your hands.</style>
<style="Body"><color="blue">Ember Deposits</color>, frozen in place, collect around openings in the ground.
A byproduct of the <style="Pyre">Pyre</style>, these energy sources have gone dormant. At closer inspection, one mound of this rubble seems to have something more powerful protruding from it.
While you could take the Protrusion, removing some of the Ember Deposits and hauling them from the area would help to eventually revive them with some power, granting you something later on.
<style="Body">You pull the glowing protrusion from the deposit pile, but doing so causes the rubble to collapse and spill into your train.
Before you have time to offload the debris, the <style="Pyre">Boneshaker</style> jolts ahead on its journey.</style>
<style="Body">You remove the ember deposits from the pile and place them into the <style="Pyre">Boneshaker</style>. They may be a burden now, but they could prove useful later on.
The train rumbles back to life, leaving the glowing relic behind for another lucky traveler.</style>
<style="Body">Similar to before, <color="orange">Ember Deposits</color> are seen piled throughout the area.

But this time, you can see the ice beginning to melt, revealing the more powerful <style="Keyword">Ember</style> beneath. As if influenced by the warming of its related energy, the <style="Keyword">Calcified Ember</style> you removed before starts to melt as well, granting you something much more useful to harness along your journey.</style>
<style="Body">The remains of <color="blue">Armageddon</color> litter the icy landscape. Both Winged and Hellborne lie peacefully in their final resting place of snow.
The train finally comes to halt near fallen soldiers from both sides. Did they really believe in what they were doing? Was either side justified in this fight?
But it's all irrelevant now. Survival is the only thing that matters. Besides, the weapons they've left behind may prove to be of some use in the battles ahead.</style>
<style="Prompt">What do you salvage from this ancient fight?</style>
<style="Body">You pull the sword from the gnarled remains. You've never felt the weight of the Winged's weapons before, but this sword is as light as a wingfeather and sharper than Railsteel.

You can only imagine the number of <style="Keyword">Hellborne</style> that have been dealt pain by this sword. And the number of <style="Keyword">Winged</style> that will soon be repaid the same.</style>
<style="Body">It takes several attempts to bring the shield into the <style="Pyre">Boneshaker</style>, but once you do you're able to marvel at the sheer size and durability of it.
It didn't seem to protect the poor soul you took it from, but hopefully it can serve you better.</style>
<style="Body">You decide to take the remains of your fellow <style="Keyword">Hellborne</style>. Even in death, there's power to be wrought from the bones of the fallen.</style>
<style="Body">More remains of <color="blue">Armageddon</color> are found in the snow, eerily similar to before.
Have you been here already? Or is the carnage so widespread that it's all become noise to you?
But you see something you've not seen before. A glowing relic amongst the dark figures. Perhaps it can help you to make this war a distant memory...</style>
<style="Body">A mysterious <color="purple">figure</color> races towards the train with the <style="Keyword">Winged</style> not far behind.
“No time to explain. Take these and hide them for me. I can't afford to be caught with them now, so I'll have to come back for them later. Don't worry you'll be compensated generously later on.”
<style="Prompt">Do you take something from the mystery man?</style>
<style="Body">“You have my thanks! And don't worry, I'll be seeing you soon.”</style>
<style="Body">“Understood, though I imagine you'll regret that decision.”</style>
<style="Body">The mysterious <color="purple">figure</color> returns, this time much more composed than last you met.

“Ah, my loyal friend! What a pleasure to see you again. Please excuse my manners from before, I was rather occupied at the time. My name is <smallcaps>Dante</smallcaps>, a collector of rare artifacts and renowned pain-in-the-ass to all those with Wings. At your service.”</style>

<style="Body">“Now I do appreciate your help in my time of need. And as promised, your well deserved reward. But it is already in your possession! Ah, those rocks may not seem like much, but take a closer look.”</style>
<style="Body">“I've no use for them anymore thanks to a rather friendly Animus, so please take them as a small sign of my gratitude.”
“And should you happen to find youself in need of assistance in matters considered, ahem, less than desirable, please do not hesitate to call upon my services again!”
<style="Body">“Now I do appreciate your help in my time of need. I was able to evade those insufferable creatures thanks to your help.”
“And for carrying the load, I'll think I'll join you, if you'll have me of course!”</style>
<style="Body">“I look forward to our work together!”</style>
<style="Body"><color=#2e2eab>The Historian</color> approaches the open door with several large books in the back of his strange carriage.
“My time in Hell has granted me access to the records of so many <anim=wave>fascinating</anim> clans. The pages have lost their value, however, as I've memorized their contents.”
“I have the records of the [InkInsert:randomclasses] at your disposal, though I can only bear to part with one for now.”</style>

<style="Body">“Good luck <style="Keyword">Hellborne!</style> May the Pyre protect us in our journeys.”</style>

<style="Body">The <style="Keyword">Boneshaker</style> stops near the abandoned remains of a train. Looking to have belonged to a <color="orange">Merchant</color>, the train still seems to have some wares.
A few remaining goods from the clans of the [InkInsert:randomclasses] are out in the open for the taking, but taking something may cause the abandoned remains to fall to pieces.

target: <style="Prompt">Which clan's artifact do you take from the collapsing train?</style>
<style="Body">You prefer not to risk the damage it may cause.</style>
<style="Body">You carefully retrieve the item from the wreckage, trying your best not to disturb the train any further...</style>
...but the train collapses under its own weight, making any other items of value impossible to obtain.
...but upon lifting the last item from the train, it collapses into a heap in the snow. Good timing.
...and after much creaking and groaning, the train continues to stand relatively intact!
<style="Body">So, you head back on your way.</style>
<style="Body"><color="red">Railspikes</color> from the Rings of Hell have been driven into a stone near the Rail like some sort of monument.

At the base lies a hammer, carved with ancient runes. You can't make it all out, but what you can talks of the Founding of the <style="Keyword">Covenant</style>. Could this be the birthplace of the Rail?

But with the <style="Keyword">Covenant</style> now broken, these spikes serve no purpose here. Many of them are lodged too deep into the stone to take, but the spikes of the [InkInsert:randomclasses] are loose enough to pry away.</style>
developer_comments:
(Group: 'ClassSpikes')

[InkInsert:randomclasses]: A list of clan names.  Example: Hellhorned, Awoken, and Melting Remnant

target: <style="Body">After quite some effort, you remove the <style="Keyword">Spike</style> from the stone, its original power still evident from the glowing runes.
With this ancient piece of the <style="Keyword">Covenant</style> now in hand, you head back on your way.</style>
<style="Body">A <color="blue">Fissure</color> in the ice forces the <style="Keyword">Boneshaker</style> to stop.
You've seen cracks like this before, often allowing you to multiply your forces through some ancient magic. But this one is different. <anim=shake>Unstable</anim>.
Throwing something into the fissure could have unusual side effects, while just absorbing the energy from afar could have the more expected effect.
<style="Prompt">How do you approach the ice fissure?</style>
<style="Body">Even from a safe distance, the energy is almost too strong to endure. But it has the intended consequence of duplicating your forces.</style>
<style="Body">Your tribute sinks into the fissure, followed by a bright flash of light...<smallcaps>Then nothing.</smallcaps> The fissure closes.
All that's left are several copies of what you tossed in. <smallcaps><anim=shake>Unstable</anim></smallcaps>, but strong.</style>
<style="Body">You see the tent before you see the <color="yellow">Winged</color> hiding near it. You prepare for a fight.

“I was left here by my so-called people. Bah! Traitors, all of 'em. And they didn't even leave me with anything to defend myself! The gall! Turns out this fight isn't as clear as we once thought, eh?”
“Perhaps you Hellborne can prove more generous than our 'friends' above? I promise to give it back to you later in perfect condition.”
<style="Prompt">Do you leave the Winged some aid?</style>
<style="Body">“I can't say I don't understand. Some cuts just run too deep, right?”
“Well, once you see <style="Keyword">Seraph</style> make sure to give 'em Hell for me. Not sure I'll make it long enough to do it myself...”</style>
<style="Body">“Thank you <style="Keyword">Hellborne</style>. I won't forget this kindness. Truly.”
“And unlike my feathered compatriots, I will keep my word.”
<style="Body">A familiar tent comes closer into view. The <style="Keyword"><color="yellow">Winged</color></style> looks eager to see you behind its curtain.

“<style="Keyword">Hellborne</style>! I'm surprised to see you back so soon. But, I'm a Wing of my word. Here you go, good as new! I even took the liberty of making it just a little better for you. Consider it a small way to begin apologizing for our long history of, uh, disagreements.”
“I could, however, hold on to it for a bit longer? Give it the ol' <style="Keyword">Winged</style> treatment.”</style>
<style="Prompt">Do you retrieve your donation now or later?</style>
<style="Body">“Wonderful! Let's consider my debt paid then. Well, er, aside from the whole invasion nonsense...”
“Give 'em Hell! And don't be afraid to rip off a wing or two, they hate that.”</style>
<style="Body">The ramshackle tent, now an oddly welcome surprise, comes into view. Safely inside, the <color="yellow">Winged</color> is patiently waiting for you.
“Well it wasn't easy, let me get that out of the way first. But this here is some of <style="Keyword">Heaven's</style> finest work if I'm being honest... and I am.”
“So make sure this gets used in the right place. <style="Keyword">Seraph</style> can smell an assault from Rings away, but I think you just might have a chance.”</style>
<style="Body">“We're not that different, you know. Just two tracks on the same rail. Let's hope we end up going the same place.”
“Best of luck, <style="Keyword">Hellborne</style>. <style="Keyword">Seraph's</style> gonna wish he'd never crossed the likes of us.”</style>
<style="Body"><color="red">Shards of the Pyre</color>, remnants of the once great beacon of Hell, are strewn about.
When it was extinguished, the shattered <style="Pyre">Pyre</style> must have been ejected through these <style="Keyword">Hellvents</style> across all 9 Rings.

Taking advantage of the opportunity, some entrepreneurial soul decided to setup a still near the <style="Keyword">Hellvent</style>, converting what energy remained into potent liquids. While the owner must have heard you coming and scrambled off, some of their product remains.</style>
<style="Body">You can tell that someone has been drinking from the open container near the still. So you make what you hope is the more sensible decision and take some of the liquid from there.
It can't be that bad. If whoever made it has been drinking it, they must still be alive!... for now.</style>
<style="Body">Why take a swig, when you can take the <smallcaps><anim=wave>entire still</anim></smallcaps>! Who knows, it might come in handy later on...</style>
<style="Body">A <color="red">Penance Yard</color> comes into view - a truly terrible sight.
Dead Hellborne from across the <style="Keyword">9 Rings of Hell</style> are strung up as atonement, just for existing.
At the base of these awful contraptions are some familiar blights, but peeking through you can see something of value underneath the rubble.</style>

<style="Body">You inspect what looks to be <style="Keyword">Ember</style> but are disappointed to find that it's been hardened into something else. Luckily, some of it has regained power over time, though in very different ways.</style>
<style="Body">It takes you some time to move the massive stones, but when you do, you're rewarded with the treasure it was hiding underneath.</style>

<style="Body">What looks like shards of the <style="Pyre">Pyre</style> are something much more sinister. You load them onto the train along with the strange, smooth shard they were hiding. It may prove useful...</style>
Illuminated by the light creeping into the cavern, you can see a figure inside. Trapped. Runes etched into the ice read:
Witness the False Prophet. Forger of the Rail and Covenant. Now Damned and Broken.
He must have been a prisoner of the <style="Keyword">Winged</style>. Poor soul. The remains of his tools are frozen nearby. Perhaps he can help you, even in death.</style>
<style="Body">You're able to melt the ice enough to retrieve the hammer. Its solid make gives you a calming assurance of the trials ahead.</style>
<style="Body">You're able to retrieve the tome from the ice, the pages still somehow dry after all this time frozen in ice.</style>
<style="Body">The locket proves difficult to pry free, not wanting to leave its owner. But when it does, you're greeted by a familiar face inside and more questions than answers.</style>
<style="Body">You leave the man behind. False Prophet or not, you have a feeling he's helped Hell more than you know.</style>
<style="Body">“Well that is unfortunate. Though I'd wager our parting will bring you much regret...”</style>
<style="Prompt">Do you help out the Bone Dog?</style>
<style="Body">A <color="white">Dog made of Bone</color> sits by a Hell Portal, its bonetail rattling together against the stone in a jerking motion you suspect is nervous wagging.

You catch glimpses of a foreign world through the portal. It's a place not of this realm but still equally hostile, and this Bone Dog seems eager to get as far away from it as possible. You wouldn't dare subject the dog to the violence of battle, but showing some kindness is a reward in itself.</style>
<style="Body">That seems to be a good enough sign as any for the Bone Dog. It licks your face and jumps aboard the Boneshaker to surely make quick friends with all the other monsters inside.</style>
<style="Body">You can't take the dog along, but you decide to leave something behind to hopefully ease your stinging guilt. As the train chugs away, you realize it didn't ease much...</style>
<style="Body">The excited rattling stops and Bone Dog lies flat on the ground. His eyeholes stare up at the train longingly as it rattles away.
<style="Body">You reach through the portal to the <style="Class6">Bogwurm's Remains</style>, close your hand around something solid, and pull it back through.</style>
<style="Body">The <color="blue"><anim=shake>shivering blacksmith</anim></color> braces against the stinging wind. From afar one would easily mistake her for a small mountain.

“It's not like I want to come out here, you know. Just - you always come by the Forge at the worst times and it's always so much business that I forget some of the other more important things I'm working on."

“Well, hrmm, anyways, I'm working on something new. A hammer of sorts. And yes, before you can ask, she'll help out you and your sorry lot. It's just, uh... well, she doesn't work like she should. Got a bit of a mind of her own. So, I figure you could take her with you and help me out for once. Just needs a little 'fine-tuning' is all. Hitting those birds around 5 times oughta do the trick."
<style="Prompt">“So, err, you up for a little 'fine-tuning'?”</style>
"Just try and be gentle with her, eh? Or, at least a little less hard on it than you usually are with these things."</style>
<style="Body">"Heh, guess it was a little foolish of me to think you'd start being the selfless type... No matter. I'll still help you out."
"And just to prove I'm still the giving one in this relationship, here's something that might help you out."
<style="Body">"Fantastic. I give. You take. And Hell keeps freezing. All as it should be..."
"Ughhh...don't mind me. It's no bother. I just get a bit gruff sometimes is all. It's just so. Damn. Cooooold."
<style="Body">"Hmmph. Figures, I suppose. Can't fix what wants to stay broken."
<style="Body">"Well, how'd she work out for you? Were you able to work out all the kinks? Here, let me take a look..."</style>
“What in Nine Rings did you do to this thing?!?”

"It looks like you tried to tear apart the Rail with it! And then when that didn't work, you ran it over with the Boneshaker to forget about it altogether! Ughhh... it's gonna take me a long time to get her back and healthy. A real long time. So, I guess I'm coming with you."
<style="Prompt">"What, you're not going to let me come???"</style>
<style="Body">"Good. And don't think this makes it okay. It is NOT okay. She just needs a little more love and a lot more polish, and I sure as hell don't trust you to do either of those things."
"At least I can take off this damn coat now..."</style>
"Fine. Well, I guess I know not to trust you with anything important again."
"Go on. Don't you have some feathered friends you're supposed to go play with?"</style>
<style="Prompt">"Why don't I help you ruffle those bastards' feathers, eh?"</style>

<style="Body">A <color="blue"><anim=shake>pillar of light</anim></color> spews strange fragments into the air making the way ahead dangerous. The Boneshaker grinds to a halt on its own, perhaps recognizing the odd power emanating from the pillar.

The air is stale, imperceptible even. No longer stinging with the outer chill, but also devoid of life entirely. You feel the urge to hold your hand to the light, unsure of what may occur, but something in the back of your mind urges caution.

<style="Body">Entranced, you reach into the unknown power and the light consumes you. Flashes of Hellborne and Humans and those of Heaven flicker past in this strange pocket realm. As if refocusing it, their lifeforce can be felt like molten brands in your head.
And looming beyond it all, a booming darkness unlike anything you've ever felt. A void of life and death and goodness. The Divinity.
When you pull your hand out, a remnant of the all-powerful Divinity comes with you.
<align="center">You know now, you are not alone.</style></align>
<style="Body">Some part of your subconscious wills you away from the light. It is powerful but unknown.
Tossing some of your own power into the pillar fragments it into smaller pieces, imbuing each one with some of the light within.</style>
<style="Prompt">Do you continue down this path with Malicka?</style>
<style="Body">The <color="red"><style="Keyword">Boneshaker</color></style> barely even stops before the scrawny Winged scavenger starts talking.

"You know, I got this feeling I can't shake that we've met already in another life. Lots o' times, in fact. Like we just keep doing this over and over and over again, but just go on resetting and forgetting. Makes you think about our existence and larger purpose here, you know? Your everyday metaphysical despair kind of stuff."
"I like it! The thinking man's strategy. Hit 'em where it hurts, right in the morals. Though, I can't really say that's worked much in the past, what with freezing Hell, mass genocide, and all..."
"But hey, I'm sure you're gonna knock 'em right in their guilty stomachs this time!"
<style="Body">"Okay, okay, I hear you! Give 'em an old-fashioned Hellborne talking to, am I right? They bring a knife, you bring a sword. They bring a big ass Winged, you bring a bigger ass Demon?"
"Look, the metaphor's a bit of a work in progress, but you get the idea. If you want 'em to hurt, you're gonna need some bite."</style>
<style="Body">"You wouldn't think it by looking at me, but I'm not much of a fighter myself. If I was though, that there's the one I'd pick."

<style="Body">An <color="yellow">Arcane Machine</color> peeks through the snow, mechanical arms and controls in various states of disrepair. The large harness in the center looks to have held something vaguely familiar, but you can't place what.
Near the opening of the train, a metal control board stands relatively untouched. Clean, even. Strange.
When you move towards it, the board whirs to life and a single button with a diamond icon flashes at you.</style>
<style="Body">The machine moans in response, additional prompts appearing on the control panel.</style>
<style="Body">A row of levers rises from the metal board, each one adorned with symbols you can only assume refer to various elemental effects.</style>

<style="Body">The buttons and levers of the control panel recede into the metal box as the entire device sinks into the ground. The metal harness clamps shut, likely trying to embrace whatever once existed in its grasp.
But as the metal arms link, the train starts to shudder. No, your Pyre starts to rumble. Perhaps in recognition?
Before any logical thought can form, a blinding flash of light knocks you back. What's left behind is a polished, black orb, not unlike the Pyre itself.</style>
<style="Body">A row of levers rises from the metal board, each one adorned with symbols you can only assume refer to various health-related effects.</style>
<style="Body">A small rod rises from a space in the board. It can be moved in 4 directions, though one direction is blocked entirely.</style>
<style="Body">Several switches appear on the board, each one decorated with a complex series of symbols you can't decipher.</style>
<style="Prompt">Do you switch any of them on?</style>
<style="Body">The mysterious woman appears before you once more, the pressure exerted from <color=#8700b3>her presence</color> as strong as before.
<style="Body">“You won’t regret this. Unless you die, in which case you might regret this. Talk to you in a bit, hopefully!”</style>
<style="Body">Malicka appears before you once more, exerting as much <color=#8700b3>unseen pressure</color> as per usual. You find it oddly comforting this time around.
<style="Body"><color=#8700b3>Malicka the Titan</color> emerges in front of you yet again, her playful demeanor replaced with a stern, solemn face.
<style="Body">A mysterious woman stands before you. You feel a strange pressure emanate from <color=#8700b3>her presence</color>.

“Thank you. With my powers, you at least have a chance to make things right. The Pact is a tricky thing, but it guarantees you an opening at the Divine. If you are successful, I may never see you again. If not, then may we meet again in the next cycle and try again…”

<style="Body">A mysterious woman stands before you, a mischievous smirk painted on her face. You feel a strange force emanate from <color=#8700b3>her presence</color>, its pressure so strong you worry the Boneshaker might collapse.
“Oh good, my entertainment is finally here!”
<style="Body">Malicka’s eyes widen, happily surprised by your resolve.
<style="Prompt">“Take as many trinkets as you can bear to carry.”</style>
“Adventurous this cycle, are we? Try to keep your wits about you and remember: Death is not the end.”
<style="Body">Malicka appears before you, surprised by the fact that you’re not yet dead. The pressure emanated by <color=#8700b3>her presence</color> continues to feel nauseating.
“How’s fighting Seraph the Whatever for the rest of eternity treating you? Don’t bother answering — I don’t actually care.”

“Instead, how about you offload some of that cargo you’re hauling? In exchange, I’ll tickle you with a little <anim=wave>mystical energy</anim> or something. We’ll see what happens after that. You in?”</style>
“Still alive? Wonderful! We’re only just beginning!”

<style="Body">The forces of hell have battled ceaselessly in defense of the Boneshaker, and you know they would greatly enjoy a drink of the dubious liquid. Their hearty constitutions are also certain to stave off any adverse effects... or so you hope.</style>
<style="Body">You sense an overwhelming presence pulse through. Like a booming power stretching through all of existence.</style>
<style="Divine"><anim=divine>“The understanding eludes me for why one with such little power as yourself continues to fight for a world that has already been condemned to die.”

“Divinities created this world. Not for you - never for you - but for us. It was a game, for the Child, to Judge souls as good or as evil. We did not care for this lowly play, but the creation of this world took less than a breath. Time was my Domain and Life was the Mother's.”</anim></style>
<style="Prompt">The Divine presence vanishes, some lingering power left behind in its wake.</style>
<style="Divine"><anim=divine>“Time has never held sway over my existence. What would pass as seconds for me are endless eternities in this world. Your existence is of little consequence.”
“And yet, you were able to take the Child and the Mother from me. I do not feel as you small beings do, but I did...contract.”

“So I've contracted Time to a circle. There is no end, only beginning again. Forever. Replace your precious Pyre or leave Hell to freeze. It has no meaning. You are doomed to repeat your struggle over and over. That is your punishment. Even my own defeat - temporary.”</anim></style>

<style="Divine"><anim=divine>“Your Pyre was created here, did you know? The Titans of the Elements, created by the Mother to carve out this very world, sacrificed at Herzal’s request and fused into the very lifeforce you carry aboard that vehicle.”

<style="Divine"><anim=divine>“The Child eventually grew tired of Judgement and bored of this Realm. So, we sent you Judges. Herzal first and Malicka soon after. We thought it best to leave you to your own survival. Ultimately, your free will led to your own demise. As well as others of Divinity.”
“Now, you are all just grains of sand in an endless desert of time.”
“Though I will admit, I have sensed a merging of late. Part of my divinity slipping away into your own soul. I suspect it to be part of our shared Pact, a consequence of the collapsing of time.”
<style="Body">A famaliar figure hunches in front of an iceberg. She stands to meet you.
<style="Divine"><anim=divine>“I do not understand the mechanics of hope, but I can respect the strength it gives.”
“Your world is of no consequence to me, and the sins committed against me are done and paid for. But I cannot allow the rules of this loop to lapse.”
“We will continue to fight, but perhaps we can fight with respect.”</anim></style>

<style="Body">“He wasn’t all bad, you know. Yeah, he was gone all the time and even when he was around he holed up by himself and wrote... all the time. But he was a good man, even if he was the worst father.”
“I try to remember that when I realize his part in this. He’s not innocent, but who really is anymore?”</style>
<style="Prompt">“If you’re destined to do this forever, might as well make him hurt for it, eh?”</style>

"He tried at least, that's more than most of us can say. But Seraph gave up. Figured he could do it all himself. Rule through force and fear. Herzal's mistakes pushed him to that end I'd wager. That makes him no better than this Divinity, even if I don't blame him for trying."</style>
<style="Body">“The world’s broken. If it’s not freezing, it’s something else. You might not break that cycle, but...you also just might.”
<style="Prompt">You feel your being begin to contract. Do you submit?</style>
<style="Body">“Great! I suppose I should tell you that these crystals likely are going to kill you, but if they do I’ll just see you in some other cycle I suppose. Ta-ta!”</style>

“I suppose now would be a good time to introduce myself. I’m Malicka, but you already knew that. Well, you would have known that if not for the loop that we’ve all been stuck in. Ugh, what a drag. The point is, forget the Pyre! What we’re up to is way more fun!”

“A Judge to be more precise. I established the Laws you see. Not laws about human morality, too much writing there. Old Herzie was much better suited for that boring affair. No, I made the Natural laws, like special relativity and the perception of Time. Though, as it turns out, these seem to be beyond my grasp as of late. Endless loops aren't quite my style.”</style>
<style="Prompt">“But with your help, and just a little touch of your life, we’ll find a way to break the Loop!”</style>
“So, please try not to. Die that is. Last time was quite disappointing.”</style>

“I could have fought back you know. Put an end to this before it even began. Instead I… I fled. Now nothing can bring back my fallen kin. Herzal, my first and maybe only friend, was like a brother to me… and I left him for dead.”</style>

“You probably don’t thanks to the Loop, but it’s Malicka, your bestie! Last time you wanted to play cards, but that was boring, so let’s try something else. I have three trinkets, all of which will make your life much worse than it already is. Take some. If they kill you, I win! If they don’t, you win!”

“Well, kudos to you for surviving this long. I’m going to take those trinkets back and give you your prize now. Maybe it’ll help you smack Seraph the Whatever into oblivion for the umpteenth time. Maybe it won’t. Either way, somebody’s going to die and I’m going to watch!”</style>
<style="Body">“When you see Seraph, tell him Malicka says hello. That’ll be sure to ruffle his literal feathers. See you next cycle!”</style>
“If Time is in a Loop, death is not the end.”
“You only won because I went easy on you!”

<style="Body"><style="Keyword">“Excellent!</style> I can't say I even know for certain what that is, but I found it deep in the Bogs so there must be something there someone wants to keep hidden.”</style>
"Honestly, who the Hell knows anymore. Everytime I look away, new factions keep popping up. Might even happen again. Who knows!"
"Maybe, just maybe, one of them will have some answers. Until then...give 'em Hell."</style>
<style="Prompt">Which direction do you shift the rod to?</style>
<style="Body">Right. Best to leave the relics of the arcane untouched. Especially those of the Pyre-shaking variety.</style>
<style="Body">“This Pact is a slippery little deal we made towards the end. It’s like an emergency safety valve to save the world, except the more you spin the wheel the more likely you are to die.”
